<subSubSection pageId="278" pageNumber="279" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="278.[189,310,611,637]" box="[189,310,611,637]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,611,637]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,611,637]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="278.[189,1399,659,757]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Thaxt." authorityName="Thaxt." box="[312,694,659,685]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Amorphomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="falagriae">
<emphasis box="[312,609,659,685]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Amorphomyces falagriae</emphasis>
Thaxt.
</taxonomicName>
, but the female thalli differ by the bulging on the perithecial margin involving second and, sometimes, also the first wall cells tiers, i.e., w 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1109,1118,714,728]" fontSize="6" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">2</subScript>
and part of the w 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1331,1340,714,728]" fontSize="6" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">1</subScript>
cell; and for straight male thalli.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1225,798,871]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="278.[189,324,798,824]" box="[189,324,798,824]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,798,824]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,798,824]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="278.[189,1225,845,871]" box="[189,1225,845,871]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">The species epithet means “inflated” and refers to the swelling of the perithecial margin.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
